Tony Blair said that he would use the opportunity to return as Britain's prime minister -- but acknowledges that a comeback is unlikely.
In an interview this evening on the occasion of the fifth anniversary of his leaving the office, the 59-year-old announced his views on various domestic political issues.
Since his resignation in June 2007 after a decade as head of state, Blair has largely avoided, mostly to comment on British politics, and his comments on foreign policy and his role as envoy of the Quartet of peacemakers in the Middle East.
On the question of whether he would like to return to the post of prime minister, Blair was quoted by the London Evening Standard, in the words: "yes, yes, but it is unlikely that this happened, so..."
